        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>How to: Animate the Position or Color of a Gradient Stop</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This example shows how to animate the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop.Color%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop.Offset%2A&gt;</ph> of <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop&gt;</ph> objects.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example animates three gradient stops inside a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The example uses three animations, each of which animates a different gradient stop:</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The first animation, a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.DoubleAnimation&gt;</ph>, animates the first gradient stop's <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop.Offset%2A&gt;</ph> from 0.0 to 1.0 and then back to 0.0.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>As a result, the first color in the gradient shifts from the left side to the right side of the rectangle and then back to the left side.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The second animation, a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.ColorAnimation&gt;</ph>, animates the second gradient stop's <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop.Color%2A&gt;</ph> from <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Colors.Purple%2A&gt;</ph> to <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Colors.Yellow%2A&gt;</ph> and then back to <ph id="ph5">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Colors.Purple%2A&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>As a result, the middle color in the gradient changes from purple to yellow and back to purple.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The third animation, another <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Animation.ColorAnimation&gt;</ph>, animates the opacity of the third gradient stop's <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop.Color%2A&gt;</ph> by -1 and then back.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>As a result, the third color in the gradient fades away and then becomes opaque again.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="113" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Although this example uses a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.LinearGradientBrush&gt;</ph>, the process is the same for animating <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.GradientStop&gt;</ph> objects inside a <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.RadialGradientBrush&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
